column47: Finance Apprenticeship (Level 3) Training
column48: The DE&S Finance Apprenticeship Scheme trains apprentices over a 2 yr program involving attainment of qualifications typical of Level 3 & 4 AAT. It includes training, assessment & practical accounting experience in a working environment within MOD Project teams. The on-job training is predominantly based in MOD Abbey Wood. For 2017 DE&S will recruit up to 30 apprentices as fixed term employees of the MOD. A contractor is required to provide a service to deliver academic and vocational training, including expert verification & moderation of apprentices training efforts & achievements. The program broadly follows the new Accounting Standard for AAT Level 3 and Accounting Framework Level 4 FR03797 covering, but not limited to the basic qualifications as follows: Phase 1 - 4 weeks basic intro to Accounting and 11 months to complete Level 3 AAT Advanced Diploma in Accounting; and Phase 2 -18 months to complete Level 4 AAT Professional Diploma in Accounting. Training must take place in suitable facilities with a 5 mile radius of MOD Abbey Wood, Bristol. The contractor is to deal with all administration associated with the draw down of any Govt subsidies such as Skills Funding Agency (SFA) funding, and/or work with the Authority in the transfer to any new funding/student loan arrangements that may be imposed by future Govt regulation or legislation. Tenders are to be submitted following the instructions given in the Defence Contracts Bulletin under Contract Notice DTEC/242.

column47: Data Centre Co-location Services
column48:
Due to external influences impacting the future operating capability of one of UCL's onsite data centre facilities, UCL has a requirement to relocate all IT services and hardware from their existing data centre to a data centre co-location provider from March 2017 for an 18 month contracted period.

As part of a large data centre transformation programme within UCL there is a significant data centre consolidation initiative underway. This initiative coupled with a demand to provide more data centre space for customers may result in change to the day one cabinet and power requirement outlined in this tender.

UCL wishes to appoint a Supplier to provide a data centre space and the related services (power, cooling, connectivity and physical security) necessary to house and provide an operating environment for physical computing infrastructure subject to maximum separation requirements from UCLs primary location in Bloomsbury. 

UCL requires the Supplier to provision diversely routed, resilient dark fibre optical connections from UCLs primary location (WC1E 6BS) to the Suppliers data centre facility either directly through the Suppliers own carrier network or via a third party telecommunications network. The optical power return loss between these two locations must be no greater than 20dB over a maximum physical distance of 10km. UCL requires the data centre facility services and connectivity to be available to ensure the migration of services can commence no later than June 2017.

column47: Early Help Service for Children and Young People
column48:
NHS Arden and Greater East Midlands Commissioning Support Unit (AG CSU), on behalf of the Commissioners, West Leicestershire Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG), East Leicestershire and Rutland CCG and Leicester City CCG, are undertaking a procurement for Early help targeted mental health and emotional wellbeing support service for young people.

The CCGs are commissioning a newly specified service from April 2017, which will provide prevention and early intervention support for issues relating to low level mental health needs and emotional wellbeing, such as anxiety, isolation and mild depression, amongst a range of other concerns.

The service will include an individual to co-ordinate the service and provide regular reporting against the KPIs and a team of practitioners to be based in localities in existing Local Authority premises within the Early Help intervention teams. Young people will be identified through early help interventions and referred into this new service. The service will deliver counselling, individual support and therapeutic group work, at a greater intensity of intervention than provided by universal family support services.

It is expected that the Provider will work in an integrated way with other primary mental health services, and voluntary and community groups will be integral to the provision of the service.

Providers are now invited to bid for the service via the Bravo portal https://ardengemcsu.bravosolution.co.uk/web/login.html

column47: Northstowe Town Centre Uses Study with Retained Advice
column48:
UPDATE: Please note the latest Q & A document has been uploaded to the HCA extranet which can be accessed via the link provided within the description section of this notice.  UPDATE 13/12/2016: Answers to tender clarification questions have been answered which can be accessed via the link to the HCA extranet tender folder.

The HCA wishes to collaborate with a consultant who can re-imagine the purpose of a town centre - one that responds to changing markets, consumer expectations, working/business practices and new technology.

Northstowe will be a new town of 10,000 homes, just 5 miles north west of Cambridge.

Northstowe will have a truly mixed-use town centre (8.5 hectares, 21 acres) starting in 2019. It will be a high-density district set around a 1.2ha town square and landscaped park.

The emerging Northstowe Economic Development Strategy (EDS) promotes a pioneering culture of learning, enterprise, innovation and flexibility.

Given this entrepreneurial vision and the HCA's commitment to creating a place with real identity - a standard approach to the town centre is unlikely to fulfil those aspirations. 

We need your expertise on emerging trends and concepts in retail, leisure, community space and office/workspace to create a town centre fit for the future. Backed-up by your knowledge of how 'conventional' mixed-use centres work and a robust statistical and qualitative methodology, you will produce a study that shows how we can create an offer that is inspiring, distinct but also financially viable.

The HCA is mindful that one consultancy may not have access to all of the expertise needed to fulfil this brief. The HCA encourages consultants to collaborate as needed to ensure the highest level of advice in each area.

Plans for the town centre are at a stage where the appointed consultant will have a unique opportunity to help shape the direction of this landmark development.

Key deliverables
 
1.	Review and Inception Report

2.	Report - Northstowe Town Centre Uses Study 

•	establish preferences of future users,
•	identify the existing floorspace demand (business and consumer),
•	conduct a gap analysis,
•	establish a unique selling proposition (USP) for the town centre,
•	translate the USP and demand information into schedules of;
o	quantum, types and location of uses, 
o	types of tenant,
o	phasing,
o	meanwhile/transition uses,
•	make recommendations on how changing trends in shopping, leisure and work/business practices should influence the town centre, 
•	how to accelerate delivery,
•	projected viability for the town centre,
3.	Retained advice

It is estimated that the HCA will engage the consultant for a 2 days per month for 12 months following the completion of the Town Centre Uses Study. 

Limitation on liability 

For this commission liability is cap

Additional information: The closing time for tenders is 1pm on 9th January  2017.

All discussions, meetings and communications will be conducted in English.  

The contract will be subject to English law.  Tenders and all supporting documents must be priced in GBP and all payments under the contract will be made in GBP.

This procurement and award is subject to the transparency arrangements being adopted by the UK Government. These arrangements include the publication of tender documentation issued by the HCA and the contract between the HCA and supplier.  Bidders should highlight any areas they consider commercially sensitive in order for the HCA to be able to honour our transparency obligations without undermining the bidders commercial interests.

Candidates are advised that the HCA is subject to the Freedom of Information Act 2000 ("The Act"). If a candidate considers that any of the information supplied as part of this procurement procedure should not be disclosed because of its commercial sensitivity, confidential or otherwise, they must, when providing this information, clearly identify the specific information they do not wish to be disclosed and clearly specify the reasons for its sensitivity. The HCA shall take such statements into consideration in the event that it receives a request pursuant to the Act which relates to the information provided by the interested party. Please note, it is insufficient to include a statement of confidentiality encompassing all the information provided in the response.

The HCA takes a zero-tolerance approach to bribery and corruption and sets high standards of impartiality, integrity and objectivity in relation to the stewardship of public funds and the management of its activities. The principles contained within this policy apply to both internal and external audiences, including anyone wishing to undertake business or engage with the HCA. Please refer to our Anti-bribery and Corruption Policy by visiting https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/anti-bribery-and-corruption-policy for further information

Wales Initial Teacher Training Provider 2017 cohort (2017 - 2019)

column47: Telemedicine Advice and Guidance Service
column48:
Hammersmith & Fulham Clinical Commissioning Group, on behalf of the CWHHE Collaboration of Clinical Commissioning Groups (CCGs) is seeking expressions of interest from sufficiently experienced organisations in order to understand market ability and appetite to provide a 24/7, 365 day per year Telemedicine-clinical support function to support care homes across Central London, West London, Hammersmith and Fulham, Hounslow and Ealing Clinical Commissioning Group areas. This facility will be introduced to approximately 70 residential and nursing homes across the geography covered by these CCGs, with a phased implementation over the three years of the programme subject to successful implementation and performance of the preceding phases. Providers expressing an interest should have previous or existing experience of delivering this type of service, and be able to evidence the capacity and workforce in place to commence provision quickly, providing immediate advice and reassurance to both clinical and non-clinical staff and if necessary, to plan for local onward referral. If considered successful, the service will extend to patients and carers living outside of nursing and residential homes in further phases. Therefore, the CCGs will work with the provider over the course of the contract to seek to increase the breadth and value of the contract to improve care for people across North West London as part of the wider Last Phase of Life Programme.

Additional information: The CCG anticipates awarding a 3 year contract with the option to extend for a further 2 years at their discretion. The anticipated annual contract value is £400,000 - £7,900,000 (subject to expansion of the programme and additional investment being agreed by the CCG). Should the CCG choose to undertake a formal procurement process, it is anticipated that a Contract Notice will be published during late January 2016, working towards full service commencement during April 2017. It is expected that the programme will be part of the End of Life Care Incubator, which offers support from Social Finance and a dedicated EOLC Incubator Advisory Board, opportunities for sharing learning with other similar UK projects, and access to funding from the Care and Wellbeing Fund, a social investment fund that supports community-based models of health and social care. Providers will be expected to work collaboratively with the EOLC Incubator and Care and Wellbeing Fund. ***Providers are invited to express their interest in this potential opportunity by returning the attached questionnaire to Toby.Hyde@nw.london.nhs.uk no later than 12.00 noon on Friday 6th January 2017*** Please note that this notice does not commit NHS Hammersmith & Fulham London CCG to undertake a formal procurement and that submission of an expression of interest is not a prerequisite to any subsequent procurement application. Response to this notice may however inform the CCG's decision on whether or not to undertake a formal tender process. Responses to this invitation may also inform how such a process may need to be designed.

column47: Domestic Abuse Refuge Support and Outreach Provision in Cambridgeshire
column48:
Cambridgeshire County Council would like to invite tenders for the provision of support within three refuges for female victims of Domestic Abuse (Lots 1-3), and for the provision of outreach support for all victims of domestic abuse in Cambridgeshire (Lot 4). 
The provider(s) for the refuges must provide safe and stable refuge for women and children fleeing high risk domestic abuse, and to support them to move into safe and secure independent accommodation.  
The provider of the outreach service must provide advice, information and support to victims of domestic abuse to enable them to stay safe and to minimise risks to the victim and any children, and enable them to cope and recover from the abuse they have experienced.  The service will work with those who are experiencing domestic abuse, whether they are still in an abusive relationship, attempting to leave or have already left the relationship, at any level of risk.

column47: Tintagel Castle New Footbridge
column48:
Construction of new pedestrian footbridge between the mainland and island wards of Tintagel Castle, to include:

Pre-Construction Stage:
The pre-construction contractor will provide expert advice on the project to include the bridge designs, construction methodology and programme. They will play a key part on the project team and help to develop a deliverable project. The aim is to work in a collaborative fashion to ensure the project develops in the best way possible, in terms of buildability, programme, quality and cost. The specific duties under the PCA are set out in the attached PCA Project Brief.

Please note, the contractor is not guaranteed the contract to deliver the bridge works. This contract is dependent on the successful negotiation of the contract sum as set in the ITT, Conditions of Contract and PCA Brief. The final contract sum will be negotiated via an open book process as described in the PCA brief and in line with the attached Government Guidance Note (Appendix 3)
	 
Construction Stage:
All ground works, inclusive of bridge foundation rock anchors, accompanying prior archaeological excavations and cliff stabilisation works.

All specialist steel work, constituting the fabrication and assembly of all bridge components. 

All associated landscape works to bridge abutments and laying of bridge deck; 

Erection of all temporary works including, site compound, proposed cable crane and any necessary adaptation of the site access roads;;

Management of the whole construction operation/site, to include interaction with the general public.

Additional information: Interested parties should register at https://in-tendhost.co.uk/english-heritage/aspx/Home to express inrerest and download tender documentaion.

column47: Design and Build of an Outdoor Children's Play Area
column48:
The Great Western Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust children's unit is looking is looking to create an exciting and stimulating play area for our inpatients and day attenders, their siblings and family to enjoy.  

The children's unit play area is situated on the 2nd floor of the main hospital building, in an enclosed area which is currently decked out with dated play equipment.  We are looking to design and build a new outdoor children's play area within this space.  

The Outdoor play area would need to complement the existing environment with a consistent theme adopted throughout and be suitable for a wide age group and range of abilities/disabilities.

Additional information: The Procurement process is being conducted via the Trust's E-Procurement portal. Interested bidders should go to https://uk.eu-supply.com/login.asp?B=NHSSW.  From this home page you can see current tender opportunities as well as being able to register as a new supplier if you've never used the portal before.
